sentence-detokenized: EU rejects German request to boycott British lamb.
Peter Blackburn
BRUSSELS 1996-08-22
The European Commission said on Thursday it disagrees with German advice to consumers to avoid British lamb until scientists have determined whether mad cow disease can be transmitted to sheep.

Germany's representative on the European Union's veterinary committee Werner Zwingmann said on Wednesday that consumers should buy sheep meat from countries other than Britain until scientific advice becomes clearer.
"We do not support any such recommendation, because we see no reason to do so," the Commission's chief spokesman, Nikolaus van der Pas, told a briefing of journalists.
He said that further scientific study is needed and that if it is found that action is needed, it should be taken by the European Union.

He said EU Agriculture Commissioner Franz Fischler's proposal last month to ban sheep brain, spleen and spinal cord from the human and animal food chain was a very concrete and proactive move to protect human health.
Fischler proposed measures at EU level after reports from Britain and France that under laboratory conditions sheep could contract bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE) - mad cow disease.

However, Fischler agreed to reconsider his proposal after the EU's Standing Veterinary Committee, national animal health officials, questioned whether such an action was justified as there was only a small risk to human health.
Spanish Agriculture Minister Loyola de Palacio had earlier accused Fischler at a meeting of EU agriculture ministers of causing undue concern through "dangerous generalisations".
Only France and Britain supported Fischler's proposal.
The EU's scientific veterinary and interdisciplinary committees are due to review the issue early next month and make recommendations to senior veterinary officials.
Sheep have long been known to be affected by scrapie, a brain-damaging disease similar to BSE, which is believed to have been transmitted to cattle through feed containing animal waste.

British livestock farmers denied on Thursday that there is a risk to human health from their sheep, but expressed concern that the German government's advice to consumers to avoid British lamb could affect consumers across Europe.
"What we have to be very careful about is how other countries follow Germany's example," National Farmers' Union of Wales (NFU) president John Lloyd Jones told BBC radio.

Bonn has led efforts to protect public health after consumer confidence collapsed in March after a British report suggested that people could contract a disease similar to mad cow disease by eating contaminated beef.
Germany imported 47,600 sheep from Britain last year, almost half of its total imports.
It imported 4,275 tonnes of British lamb, about 10% of total imports.
A rare draft of a Hendrix song sells for nearly $17,000.
A rare early handwritten early draft of a song by American guitar legend Jimmy Hendrix sold Thursday for nearly $17,000 at an auction of the late musician's favorite artifacts.
A Florida restaurant paid 10,925 pounds ($16,935) for a draft of "Ain't no telling", which Hendrix wrote on a London hotel stationery in late 1966.
At the end of a concert in January 1967 in the English city of Nottingham, he threw the sheet of paper into the audience, where it was retrieved by a fan.
The buyers also snapped up 16 other items put up for auction by Hendrix's ex-girlfriend Kathy Etchingham, who lived with him from 1966 to 1969.
Among them is a black lacquer box with a pearl inlay used by Hendrix to store his drugs, which was bought by an anonymous Australian buyer for 5,060 pounds ($7,845).
The guitarist died of a drug overdose in 1970 at the age of 27.
China says Taiwan is spoiling the atmosphere for talks.
BEIJING 1996-08-22
China accused Taipei on Thursday of spoiling the atmosphere for the resumption of talks in the Taiwan Strait with Taiwan Vice President Lien Chan's visit to Ukraine this week that angered Beijing.

Speaking a few hours after Chinese state media reported that it was time to start political talks with Taiwan, Foreign Ministry spokesman Shen Guofang told Reuters, "The necessary atmosphere for the start of talks was disrupted by the Taiwanese authorities."
State media reported that China's top negotiator with Taipei, Tang Subei, told a group of Taiwanese visitors on Wednesday that it is time for the rivals to hold political talks.
"Now is the time for both sides to engage in political talks...
which is to end the state of hostility," Tang told Thursday's overseas edition of People's Daily.

The Foreign Ministry's Shen said in an interview with Reuters Television that he had read the reports of Tang's comments, but did not give details of why the negotiator thought it was time for talks with Taiwan, which Beijing considers a breakaway province.
China, which has long opposed all efforts by Taipei to gain greater international recognition, was angered by the visit of Taiwan's Vice President Lien to Ukraine this week.
China says it is the right time for talks with Taiwan.
BEIJING 1996-08-22
China said it is time for political talks with Taiwan and that the rival island should take practical steps in this direction.

Consultations should be held to determine the timing and format of the talks, the official Xinhua news agency reported late Wednesday, according to Tang Subei, executive vice president of the Association for Taiwan Straits Relations.
German car registrations in July increased by 14.2% per year.
FRANKFURT 1996-08-22
German motor vehicle registrations for the first time rose by 14.2 percent in July this year compared with the same period last year, the Federal Motor Transport Authority said on Thursday.
The bureau reported that 356,725 new cars - 304,850 passenger cars and 15,613 trucks - were registered in July 1996.
The figures represent an increase of 13.6% for passenger cars and a decrease of 2.2% for trucks since July 1995.
Motorcycle registrations increased by 32.7 percent during this period.
The increase was partly due to an increased number of Germans buying German cars abroad, while manufacturers said domestic demand was weak, the federal agency said.
Almost all German car manufacturers recorded an increase in registration numbers during this period.
Volkswagen AG won 77,719 registrations, just over a quarter of the total.
Opel AG together with General Motors came in second place with 49,269 registrations, 16.4% of the total.
Ford was third with 35,563 registrations, or 11.7%.
Only Seat and Porsche had fewer registrations in July 1996 than in July last year.
Seat recorded 3420 registrations compared to 5522 registrations in July last year.
Porsche registrations fell to 554 from 643.

Israel downplays fears of war with Syria.
Colleen Siegel
JERUSALEM 1996-08-22
Israel's outgoing peace negotiator with Syria said Thursday that the current tensions between the two countries appear to be a tempest in a teacup.
Itamar Rabinovich, who as Israel's ambassador in Washington conducted fruitless negotiations with Syria, told Israel Radio that it seems that Damascus wants to talk rather than fight.
"It seems to me that the {(1)[MISC] Syrian priority} is still the negotiation.
The Syrians are confused, they're certainly tense, but the general assessment here in Washington is that it's basically a storm in a cup of tea," he said.
Rabinowitz completes his term of office as ambassador.
He will be replaced by Eliahu Ben-Elissar, former Israeli envoy to Egypt and a politician from the right-wing Likud party.
Israel sent a message to Syria on Wednesday, through Washington, saying that it is committed to peace and wants to start negotiations without preconditions.
However, he accused Damascus of creating what he called a dangerous atmosphere.
Syria accused Israel on Wednesday of launching a hysterical campaign against it after Israeli television reported that Damascus had recently test-fired a missile.
It said its arms purchases were for defence purposes.

"The message we sent to (Syrian President Hafez al-) Assad is that Israel is ready at any time without preconditions to start peace negotiations," Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy said in an interview with Israel Radio.
Tensions have risen since Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu took office in June, promising to retain the Golan Heights that Israel seized from Syria in the 1967 Middle East war.
Israeli-Syrian peace talks have been deadlocked over the Golan since 1991, despite the previous government's willingness to make concessions in the Golan.
Peace talks between the two sides were last held in February.
"The voices coming out of Damascus are bad, not good.
The media...
are full of expressions and statements that should be of concern...
this artificial atmosphere is very dangerous because those who spread it can become its prisoners," Levy said.
"We expect Syria, if its face is towards peace, to respond to Israel's message to start peace negotiations, because that is our goal," he said. "
We don't want war, God forbid.
No one benefits from wars. "
Israeli TV Channel Two said that Damascus had sent a "calming message" to Israel.
He gave no source for the report.
Representatives of Netanyahu and Levi said they could not confirm this.
The television also reported that Netanyahu sent messages to reassure Syria through Cairo, the United States and Moscow.
Polish diplomat denies that nurses were trapped in Libya.
TUNISIA 1996-08-22

A Polish diplomat on Thursday denied a report in this week's Polish tabloid that Libya is refusing to grant exit visas to 100 Polish nurses trying to return home after working in the North African country.
"That's not true.

To date, we are not aware of any nurses who have been trapped or detained in Libya against their will, and we have not received any complaints," Tadeusz Awdankiewicz, head of the Polish embassy in Tripoli, told Reuters by phone.

Poland's labour ministry said this week it would send a team to Libya to investigate, but Awdankiewicz said the investigation was prompted by some nurses protesting about their working conditions, including non-payment of their wages.
He said that there are an estimated 800 Polish nurses working in Libya.
Two Iranian opposition leaders meet in Baghdad.
Hassan Hafidh
BAGHDAD 1996-08-22
An Iranian exile group based in Iraq pledged on Thursday to extend its support to Iran's Kurdish rebels after they were attacked by Iranian troops deep inside Iraq last month.

A statement from the Mujahideen Khalq said that its leader Massoud Rajavi met in Baghdad with Secretary General of the Kurdistan Democratic Party of Iran (KDPI) Hassan Rastegar on Wednesday and expressed support for Iran's Kurdish rebels.
"Rajavi stressed that the Iranian resistance will continue to stand by its Kurdish compatriots and the resistance movement in Iranian Kurdistan," it said.
A spokesman for the group said the meeting "marks a new level of cooperation between the Mujahideen Khalq and the Iranian Kurdish opposition".
In July, Iran heavily bombed targets in northern Iraq in pursuit of KDPI insurgents based in Iraqi Kurdish areas outside the control of the Baghdad government.
The Iraqi Kurdish areas bordering Iran are under the control of rebels of the Iraqi Kurdish group Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK).
The PUK and the Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP), the two main Iraqi Kurdish factions, have been in control of northern Iraq since Iraqi forces were driven out of Kuwait in the 1991 Gulf War.
Clashes between the two sides erupted over the weekend, in the most serious clashes since the US-sponsored ceasefire last year.
Mujahideen Khalq said that Iranian troops also bombed KDP positions in Qasri district in Suleimaniya province near the Iranian border over the past two days.
He said about 100 Iraqi Kurds were killed or wounded in the attack.
Both Iran and Turkey are launching air and ground strikes on targets in northern Iraq in pursuit of their own Kurdish rebels.
A US-led air force in southern Turkey is protecting Iraqi Kurds from possible attacks by Baghdad troops.
Saudi Arabian rial exchange rates are stable in quiet summer trade.
The Saudi rial's exchange rate against the dollar and interbank rial deposit rates remained mostly stable this week in quiet summer trading, traders in the kingdom said.
"There were no changes in the prices of Saudi rials.
The market was very quiet because of the summer holidays," said a trader.
The spot rial was placed at 3.7504 / 06 to the dollar.
One-month interbank deposits were at 5-1/2, 3/8%, three-month deposits at 5-5/8, 1/2% and six-month deposits at 5-3/4, 5/8%.
One-year funds were at six, 5-7/8 percent.
Israel approves Arafat's flight to the West Bank.
JERUSALEM 1996-08-22
Israel on Thursday gave Palestinian President Yasser Arafat permission to fly over its territory into the West Bank, ending a brief crisis between Israel and the PLO, an Arafat adviser said.
"The problem is over.
The president's aircraft has been cleared to pass through Israeli airspace, but the president is not expected to travel to the West Bank before Monday," Nabil Abu Redaina told Reuters.

Arafat was scheduled to meet with former Israeli Prime Minister Shimon Peres in the West Bank city of Ramallah on Thursday, but the venue was changed to Gaza after Israel refused to allow the Palestinian leader's helicopters to fly.
Palestinian officials accused right-wing Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of trying to stop the Ramallah meeting by keeping Arafat pinned down.
Arafat then cancelled a meeting between Israelis and PLO officials on political matters at the Allenby Bridge crossing between Jordan and the West Bank.
Abu Rdainah said Arafat had decided not to fly to the West Bank on Thursday, after Israel lifted the ban, because he had a busy schedule in Gaza and would not be free until Monday.
Arafat will meet Peres in Gaza after the no-fly zone.
JERUSALEM 1996-08-22

Yasser Arafat will meet with Shimon Peres in Gaza on Thursday after Palestinians said the right-wing Israeli government banned the Palestinian leader from flying to the West Bank for talks with the former prime minister.
